00:12:28,304 --> 00:12:30,145
by being explicit about the mission,

246
00:12:30,505 --> 00:12:31,925
but then hopefully deliver even more

247
00:12:32,106 --> 00:12:34,646
to kind of surpass people's expectations

248
00:12:34,726 --> 00:12:35,487
that we've established.

249
00:12:38,266 --> 00:12:46,930
One final thing I wanted to talk about in relation to affordances is this kind of running joke or recurring idea that players don't look up in level design.

250
00:12:47,870 --> 00:12:50,531
And the thing is that while players...

251
00:12:51,515 --> 00:12:54,557
looking up has become kind of slightly trickiest since the big

252
00:12:54,878 --> 00:12:57,459
kind of make mainstream make it me to us consoles and controllers

253
00:12:58,440 --> 00:13:01,382
and you know we kind of know that this isn't true in the case of certain games

254
00:13:01,902 --> 00:13:05,144
for example in dishonored you know plays the couple the time because they're in a

255
00:13:05,204 --> 00:13:06,045
stealth situation

256
00:13:06,585 --> 00:13:10,828
and the very mobile and we teach players that being in high ground is very safe

257
00:13:10,948 --> 00:13:12,549
and it's very useful for like

258
00:13:13,030 --> 00:13:17,813
surveying this the situation and second of example players look up in Titanfall

259
00:13:18,353 --> 00:13:19,514
especially multiplayer

260
00:13:20,192 --> 00:13:22,835
because they're always looking for opportunities to run on walls,

261
00:13:22,976 --> 00:13:24,618
they're getting sniped at from rooftops,

262
00:13:25,158 --> 00:13:27,581
and of course there are like 50-foot robots blowing things up.

263
00:13:27,601 --> 00:13:29,483
So you're going to look up all the time in that game.

264
00:13:30,375 --> 00:13:32,276
And kind of on a more moment to moment basis,

265
00:13:32,296 --> 00:13:34,938
you know, players look up when they go up a staircase.

266
00:13:35,138 --> 00:13:37,659
They look up if they're in a small room,

267
00:13:37,679 --> 00:13:39,180
but there are cables hanging from the ceiling.

268
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:42,582
A pipe above the player gushing water onto the floor

269
00:13:42,602 --> 00:13:43,342
would make them look up.

270
00:13:44,263 --> 00:13:45,664
Maybe if they were in a dark room

271
00:13:46,084 --> 00:13:47,405
and the only light source is above them,

272
00:13:47,465 --> 00:13:50,526
they would naturally look up at the light source.

273
00:13:50,666 --> 00:13:53,668
So the lesson here is that when players aren't looking up,

274
00:13:54,408 --> 00:13:55,789
The problem isn't like players,

275
00:13:56,089 --> 00:13:58,269
the players or the human nature or anything like that.

276
00:13:58,709 --> 00:14:01,730
It's actually like affordances that have kind of emerged

277
00:14:01,770 --> 00:14:02,870
without us knowing perhaps.

278
00:14:03,770 --> 00:14:05,611
You know, and if the players aren't looking up,

279
00:14:05,651 --> 00:14:08,051
it's either like maybe we can redesign

280
00:14:09,272 --> 00:14:10,972
the way we present the situation they're in

281
00:14:11,032 --> 00:14:12,192
to kind of teach them to look up.

282
00:14:12,832 --> 00:14:15,273
Or perhaps we're fighting kind of higher level affordances

283
00:14:15,313 --> 00:14:17,353
where the game, maybe the rest of the game

284
00:14:17,393 --> 00:14:18,854
has taught them that this isn't a game

285
00:14:18,874 --> 00:14:19,654
where you need to look up.

286
00:14:20,214 --> 00:14:21,594
And people are kind of like just running

287
00:14:21,614 --> 00:14:23,155
with that higher level affordance

288
00:14:23,175 --> 00:14:23,895
from the rest of the game.

289
00:14:26,416 --> 00:14:29,940
And so the reason I talk about phone says is because of how

290
00:14:30,320 --> 00:14:32,702
they relate to the subject of the talk with topic which is

291
00:14:33,183 --> 00:14:34,144
player intentionality

292
00:14:34,945 --> 00:14:38,568
and because the phone says a crucial to facilitate this idea of

293
00:14:38,708 --> 00:14:39,609
play intentionality.

294
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:42,032
It's a quick set.

295
00:14:42,912 --> 00:14:47,357
This idea of intentionality in games seems to have been coined around 1997, I

296
00:14:47,477 --> 00:14:49,619
think, partly by Doug Church who did a talk.

297
00:14:50,698 --> 00:14:52,699
and an essay on gamma sutra called

298
00:14:52,779 --> 00:14:54,099
Formal Abstract Design Tools,

299
00:14:54,680 --> 00:14:55,700
which you can still read online,

300
00:14:55,900 --> 00:14:57,581
and a book by Janet Murray called

301
00:14:58,021 --> 00:14:58,861
Hamlet on the Holodeck,

302
00:14:58,881 --> 00:15:01,002
which kind of explored this in terms of narrative,

303
00:15:01,202 --> 00:15:02,062
an interactive narrative.

304
00:15:06,004 --> 00:15:08,165
So, there's lots of fancier definitions

305
00:15:08,185 --> 00:15:09,686
that you can Google of this,

306
00:15:09,726 --> 00:15:12,707
but my version is that acting of intentionality

307
00:15:12,827 --> 00:15:14,107
is making conscious choices

308
00:15:14,728 --> 00:15:16,708
with specific goals and expectations in mind.

309
00:15:18,156 --> 00:15:19,717
And this might sound like super basic,

310
00:15:19,918 --> 00:15:21,199
like something we can take for granted

311
00:15:21,239 --> 00:15:22,860
that players are just naturally doing all the time

312
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:23,481
when you play a game,

313
00:15:24,481 --> 00:15:25,762
but it's often kind of not the case

314
00:15:25,923 --> 00:15:30,206
and often because of kind of maybe slightly wonky choices

315
00:15:30,246 --> 00:15:31,447
in the level design and that kind of thing.

316
00:15:32,428 --> 00:15:34,390
So here's some examples of weak intentionality

317
00:15:34,430 --> 00:15:36,452
that we've kind of probably all experienced at some point.

318
00:15:36,472 --> 00:15:40,255
You know, being lost and trying to find something to do

319
00:15:40,275 --> 00:15:43,137
or trying to figure out what's going on is, of course,

320
00:15:43,197 --> 00:15:45,279
not really acting with a strong sense of intentionality,

321
00:15:45,379 --> 00:15:46,720
just kind of wandering around aimlessly.

322
00:15:47,841 --> 00:15:51,307
And kind of a mod doing something without knowing why you're doing it,

323
00:15:51,748 --> 00:15:54,593
but only because either the game's UI has told you to do it

324
00:15:55,314 --> 00:15:57,117
or because it seems like the only thing you can do

325
00:15:57,137 --> 00:15:59,822
or because you think it's what the designer wants you to do.

326
00:16:00,818 --> 00:16:03,579
or you know that that thing where you find a lever in a game and you pull the

327
00:16:03,619 --> 00:16:06,420
lever because it's a lever in a video game and you're always supposed to pull

328
00:16:06,440 --> 00:16:07,240
leaves in video games.

329
00:16:07,840 --> 00:16:10,001
That's not acting with intentionality, that's kind of lame, right.

330
00:16:10,601 --> 00:16:14,502
And finally like twitch reacting to sudden surprises is not really

331
00:16:15,242 --> 00:16:18,623
you know if a monster jumps out at you from behind a door you've just opened

332
00:16:19,263 --> 00:16:22,164
it's more of an instinctive response and not an intentional kind of

333
00:16:22,924 --> 00:16:24,625
you know choice, you know.

334
00:16:25,165 --> 00:16:26,285
So that doesn't really count as

335
00:16:26,765 --> 00:16:28,226
intentionality as far as we're concerned.

336
00:16:29,190 --> 00:16:32,676
And the thing is that enabling player intentionality

337
00:16:32,856 --> 00:16:35,080
is at the heart of all immersive sim gameplay,

338
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:38,045
and the way that systems and level design is approached.

339
00:16:38,666 --> 00:16:41,891
To us, this is the whole point of presenting these gameplay

340
00:16:42,032 --> 00:16:43,093
challenges and stuff to the player.

341
00:16:44,644 --> 00:16:51,009
So this is why in Dishonored, all of the gameplay mechanics

342
00:16:51,029 --> 00:16:54,491
and abilities revolving around this idea of giving the player

343
00:16:54,591 --> 00:16:57,614
unique and combinable powers, like blinking and bend time

344
00:16:57,654 --> 00:16:59,695
and all this stuff, that encourages players

345
00:16:59,715 --> 00:17:01,457
to come up with their own ways of solving problems

346
00:17:01,517 --> 00:17:04,499
and overcoming obstacles.

347
00:17:04,539 --> 00:17:06,401
Going back to the screenshot of the Edge of the World mission

348
00:17:06,441 --> 00:17:06,861
in Dishonored 2.

349
00:17:08,184 --> 00:17:11,090
All of these affordances that we were talking about are trying to present the player

350
00:17:12,953 --> 00:17:14,857
information about their situation so that they can

351
00:17:15,298 --> 00:17:18,664
understand their options in relation to their goals and formulate a plan

352
00:17:19,004 --> 00:17:20,327
and then act with intentionality.

353
00:17:21,725 --> 00:17:24,027
This concept of intentionality is so important at Arkane

354
00:17:24,067 --> 00:17:24,987
that as a level designer,

355
00:17:25,588 --> 00:17:28,590
if you suggest a gameplay challenge or an optional puzzle

356
00:17:29,090 --> 00:17:31,251
that seems like it's kind of lacking intentionality

357
00:17:31,652 --> 00:17:34,133
at any point of the way, the idea will just be rejected.

358
00:17:34,153 --> 00:17:37,335
Like it's just bad level design as far as we're concerned.

359
00:17:37,355 --> 00:17:40,477
And wherever possible, we probably slip up sometimes,

360
00:17:40,517 --> 00:17:42,899
but wherever possible, we always want the player

361
00:17:42,919 --> 00:17:44,560
to be acting with intentionality by default.

362
00:17:47,030 --> 00:17:48,372
So to break the concept down a little,

363
00:17:48,572 --> 00:17:51,194
these are the four things that I think players need in order

364
00:17:51,234 --> 00:17:52,275
to act with intentionality.

365
00:17:53,036 --> 00:17:55,137
First of all is choice, the presentation of a choice.

366
00:17:56,318 --> 00:17:58,761
Second is motivation, having goals in mind.

367
00:17:59,561 --> 00:18:01,203
The third one is information that they

368
00:18:01,223 --> 00:18:03,805
garner from clear and consistent affordances.

369
00:18:04,445 --> 00:18:07,408
And finally, you need time to process that information.

370
00:18:07,448 --> 00:18:08,829
You can't pressure the player too much

371
00:18:09,570 --> 00:18:12,232
in order to distract them from the information

372
00:18:12,272 --> 00:18:12,913
that they need to have.

373
00:18:14,274 --> 00:18:16,215
And with those in mind, here are some ways

374
00:18:16,275 --> 00:18:18,117
of facilitating intentionality.

375
00:18:19,478 --> 00:18:21,259
First of all, it's the clear and consistent advances

376
00:18:21,279 --> 00:18:21,939
that I've talked about.

377
00:18:23,521 --> 00:18:26,763
Second of all, it really helps if you present the player

378
00:18:26,783 --> 00:18:28,664
with higher level and longer term goals,

379
00:18:28,824 --> 00:18:31,226
instead of kind of drip feeding them lower level tasks,

380
00:18:31,286 --> 00:18:33,347
like look over here, and walk in that room,

381
00:18:33,387 --> 00:18:34,148
and press this button.

382
00:18:34,788 --> 00:18:36,790
It's way cooler to just give them

383
00:18:37,190 --> 00:18:39,772
a higher level objective, which they

384
00:18:39,792 --> 00:18:40,973
can find their own solution to.

385
00:18:41,902 --> 00:18:44,364
And of course this is how Dishonored always works.

386
00:18:44,384 --> 00:18:45,726
The textbook Dishonored mission is,

387
00:18:46,246 --> 00:18:47,247
you're at this part of the map

388
00:18:47,427 --> 00:18:48,729
and somewhere on the other side of the map

389
00:18:48,809 --> 00:18:50,571
is some bad guy you've got to kill

390
00:18:50,951 --> 00:18:52,373
and it's up to you how you do it.

391
00:18:52,593 --> 00:18:54,075
And it's up to you to explore

392
00:18:54,115 --> 00:18:55,916
and find your own journey towards that goal.

393
00:18:58,195 --> 00:19:02,060
Finally, there's this idea of player-driven pacing and player-initiated action.

394
00:19:03,121 --> 00:19:04,202
It's generally...

395
00:19:04,803 --> 00:19:06,725
Again, it relates to the idea that players need time

396
00:19:06,805 --> 00:19:10,229
to take in the information and formulate a plan.

397
00:19:10,730 --> 00:19:14,494
It's just way cooler if you can find ways of giving the player space

398
00:19:14,574 --> 00:19:16,416
to act intentionally.

399
00:19:17,868 --> 00:19:20,609
And with this in mind we can consider a kind of a 4 step

400
00:19:20,669 --> 00:19:23,090
cycle of a kind of a game play cycle.

401
00:19:23,450 --> 00:19:26,311
I'm not sure who originally came up with this to be honest,

402
00:19:26,371 --> 00:19:29,212
it's been mentioned in other talks at GDC

403
00:19:29,272 --> 00:19:32,453
like by Clint Hawking, Nels Anderson, Forrest Darling

404
00:19:32,473 --> 00:19:33,253
have all talked about this.

405
00:19:34,813 --> 00:19:38,554
But yeah, it can be useful to consider this loop as something

406
00:19:38,574 --> 00:19:40,615
that the player continuously goes through as they play.

407
00:19:41,255 --> 00:19:43,456
So if we start at the top with observing,

408
00:19:44,256 --> 00:19:45,496
the player is taking in information

409
00:19:45,536 --> 00:19:46,296
about their situation.

410
00:19:47,123 --> 00:19:49,084
And then they use that information and combine it

411
00:19:49,104 --> 00:19:51,665
with their goals and their motivations to form a plan.

412
00:19:52,806 --> 00:19:53,966
Then they execute the plan.

413
00:19:54,547 --> 00:19:57,028
And then perhaps there's a fourth step

414
00:19:57,068 --> 00:20:00,269
where they react, perhaps instinctively,

415
00:20:00,329 --> 00:20:04,071
to maybe the plan not going to as they thought it would,

416
00:20:04,231 --> 00:20:08,733
or reacting to some emergent situations that arise from it.

417
00:20:09,453 --> 00:20:11,174
And then they go back to observing, of course.

418
00:20:11,214 --> 00:20:12,394
And there's just this constant cycle

419
00:20:12,414 --> 00:20:14,815
of taking in information, formulating plans,

420
00:20:15,295 --> 00:20:16,536
and acting with those plans in mind.

421
00:20:18,456 --> 00:20:20,818
And of course, stealth gameplay is particularly good

422
00:20:20,838 --> 00:20:21,878
at emphasizing this loop.

423
00:20:24,280 --> 00:20:26,261
It's built into stealth games that the player starts

424
00:20:26,321 --> 00:20:28,463
in a hidden state, where they then have time

425
00:20:28,503 --> 00:20:31,225
to think and explore and analyze the situation,

426
00:20:31,745 --> 00:20:34,087
and then formulate an intention before they reveal themselves.

427
00:20:34,127 --> 00:20:36,448
And they have to start thinking in a more dynamic way.

428
00:20:37,844 --> 00:20:39,765
And as I said before, in Dishonored,

429
00:20:39,845 --> 00:20:42,967
we use a combination of player mobility and verticality

430
00:20:43,487 --> 00:20:45,869
in our layouts to empower the player to reach safer,

431
00:20:46,129 --> 00:20:48,310
higher places that give them more time

432
00:20:48,350 --> 00:20:50,611
and a better perspective for their observation and planning

433
00:20:50,651 --> 00:20:50,991
phases.

434
00:20:52,932 --> 00:20:54,973
But a crucial point here is that you don't need to be making

435
00:20:54,993 --> 00:20:58,095
a stealth game to kind of facilitate intentionality.

436
00:20:59,156 --> 00:21:02,477
This is a screenshot of Doom 2 on the left, which I love

437
00:21:02,497 --> 00:21:05,399
dearly, and Doom 3, which I was a little bit less keen on.

438
00:21:06,159 --> 00:21:06,259
And

439
00:21:07,117 --> 00:21:10,019
Dooms 3, the thing was partly because of its move

440
00:21:10,059 --> 00:21:12,020
towards a scary horror game kind of vibe.

441
00:21:12,981 --> 00:21:15,042
It had a lot of monsters kind of popping out of nowhere

442
00:21:15,142 --> 00:21:17,344
and trying to eat your face and that kind of thing.

443
00:21:17,484 --> 00:21:20,746
And often it would like teleport monsters behind you

444
00:21:21,186 --> 00:21:22,567
after like doing something arbitrary,

445
00:21:22,607 --> 00:21:24,948
like picking up some ammo or pulling a lever

446
00:21:24,988 --> 00:21:25,609
or something like that.

447
00:21:26,449 --> 00:21:27,970
And this kind of works for the horror vibe

448
00:21:28,330 --> 00:21:29,291
that it was going for.

449
00:21:30,031 --> 00:21:31,972
But the kind of flip side to this

450
00:21:32,033 --> 00:21:33,994
is that this reliance on frequent surprises.

451
00:21:35,040 --> 00:21:36,742
where the player has no way of knowing what's going on

452
00:21:36,802 --> 00:21:38,223
until it's in their face,

453
00:21:39,004 --> 00:21:41,086
it has a side effect of killing a lot of the player's ability

454
00:21:41,146 --> 00:21:42,267
to act with intentionality.

455
00:21:43,028 --> 00:21:45,790
And it's kind of reduced to very short-term twitchy responses

456
00:21:45,850 --> 00:21:47,492
to things that they didn't expect.

457
00:21:48,643 --> 00:21:51,504
Now, Doom 2 generally had some of these surprises too.

458
00:21:51,544 --> 00:21:53,705
Sometimes you would open a door and a pinkie's in your face,

459
00:21:53,865 --> 00:21:54,445
and that kind of thing.

460
00:21:54,945 --> 00:21:57,806
But as well, it also offered way more situations

461
00:21:57,866 --> 00:22:00,967
where the player was in a much bigger area

462
00:22:01,007 --> 00:22:03,547
where they had time to consider the situation

463
00:22:03,587 --> 00:22:05,608
and always choose which weapon they wanted to use

464
00:22:05,648 --> 00:22:07,108
against these set of monsters I've seen.

465
00:22:08,029 --> 00:22:12,254
And also in the screenshot on the left, which is from a classic level called Barrels of Fun,

466
00:22:13,395 --> 00:22:17,120
it would even use setups where enemies were facing away from the player.

467
00:22:17,160 --> 00:22:22,527
So it was almost like they managed to find ways to almost implement a kind of stealth-like approach to the game,

468
00:22:23,288 --> 00:22:26,992
where you can see the situation before anyone even knows you're there.

469
00:22:29,279 --> 00:22:32,061
A final point about intentionality is that it affects

470
00:22:32,101 --> 00:22:34,583
how players perceive linearity in level design.

471
00:22:35,363 --> 00:22:37,665
Generally, I would say if linearity feels bad,

472
00:22:38,385 --> 00:22:40,287
part of the reason at least is often

473
00:22:40,327 --> 00:22:42,988
because the intentionality is kind of lacking or a little weak.

474
00:22:44,549 --> 00:22:46,431
I mentioned earlier that Half-Life 2

475
00:22:46,491 --> 00:22:47,692
is one of my favorite games of all time.

476
00:22:48,332 --> 00:22:50,614
One of the things that people often praise it for

477
00:22:51,174 --> 00:22:53,756
is this idea that it does a really good job

478
00:22:53,776 --> 00:22:55,657
of feeling a lot less linear than it really is.

479
00:22:56,743 --> 00:22:58,704
And I think there's a lot of reasons for this, you know,

480
00:22:58,744 --> 00:23:01,025
an engaging story with well-written characters

481
00:23:01,105 --> 00:23:01,846
helps a lot.

482
00:23:02,726 --> 00:23:04,867
But yeah, like I say, intentionality I think explains

483
00:23:04,947 --> 00:23:05,727
some of this as well.

484
00:23:06,808 --> 00:23:08,748
The thing is here is that Valve have play-tested

485
00:23:08,768 --> 00:23:11,469
their levels so much and iterated on their affordances

486
00:23:12,290 --> 00:23:15,211
so much that in general, they've managed to align

487
00:23:15,351 --> 00:23:17,232
what the player wants to do with the thing

488
00:23:17,272 --> 00:23:18,052
that they have to do.

489
00:23:19,133 --> 00:23:20,633
And so even though the game is linear,

490
00:23:20,733 --> 00:23:22,054
it rarely feels like you're doing things

491
00:23:22,094 --> 00:23:24,335
without knowing why, or just because the game told you to.

492
00:23:26,853 --> 00:23:29,634
On a similar note, Portal is even more linear than Half-Life 2.

493
00:23:30,374 --> 00:23:33,415
And yet, generally speaking, very few people complained about it being linear.

494
00:23:34,296 --> 00:23:37,157
It's because even though there's usually only one solution to progress,

495
00:23:37,977 --> 00:23:41,098
being a puzzle game and all, the player is given the time and the freedom

496
00:23:41,679 --> 00:23:45,040
and just the right information to constantly experiment with the Portal gun

497
00:23:45,480 --> 00:23:48,101
with intentionality in order to solve that solution.

