745
00:35:38,573 --> 00:35:43,798
don't think this is a really good phrase for us to use as a guiding principle, and I think

746
00:35:43,818 --> 00:35:44,679
we should be careful about it.

747
00:35:45,740 --> 00:35:48,041
It's useful for a lot of aspects of level design,

748
00:35:48,101 --> 00:35:49,182
like the world building stuff,

749
00:35:49,822 --> 00:35:51,643
in the sense that it encourages people to think

750
00:35:51,944 --> 00:35:54,065
about communicating stuff visually

751
00:35:54,105 --> 00:35:56,146
and in the world in front of the player, which is cool.

752
00:35:57,267 --> 00:35:58,787
And not just using cut scenes

753
00:35:58,848 --> 00:36:00,909
and big blocks of text and stuff like that.

754
00:36:01,689 --> 00:36:03,610
But my argument would be that specifically

755
00:36:03,630 --> 00:36:06,372
in terms of like interactive narrative,

756
00:36:07,152 --> 00:36:10,074
only showing and telling things is just not the full thing.

757
00:36:10,094 --> 00:36:11,195
We need to do more than that.

758
00:36:12,770 --> 00:36:15,031
And the reason why this phrase is kind of problematic

759
00:36:15,071 --> 00:36:16,851
is because we've lifted it from passive mediums

760
00:36:16,911 --> 00:36:18,772
like films and novels,

761
00:36:19,812 --> 00:36:22,993
and which don't need to worry about interactivity at all.

762
00:36:23,593 --> 00:36:25,753
So with that said, I think we can get somewhere

763
00:36:25,773 --> 00:36:27,353
that's more useful to us if we look at

764
00:36:27,794 --> 00:36:29,534
what this phrase means to those mediums

765
00:36:29,914 --> 00:36:31,454
rather than focusing on the phrase itself.

766
00:36:33,095 --> 00:36:34,895
So to explain what I mean by this,

767
00:36:35,535 --> 00:36:38,736
in film, show, don't tell is generally about this idea

768
00:36:38,756 --> 00:36:41,436
of telling the story using the unique strength of the medium.

769
00:36:42,074 --> 00:36:44,896
which in the case of film is moving pictures and editing between them

770
00:36:45,577 --> 00:36:48,320
in a way that creates drama and evokes ideas.

771
00:36:50,662 --> 00:36:52,003
In literature, by contrast,

772
00:36:52,944 --> 00:36:56,688
Show, Don't Tell is about the idea of writing in a way that evokes ideas and drama

773
00:36:57,148 --> 00:36:59,291
in the reader's mind and imagination.

774
00:37:00,850 --> 00:37:03,632
So instead of simply telling the reader things like,

775
00:37:04,153 --> 00:37:05,914
John was very sad when he said goodbye,

776
00:37:05,934 --> 00:37:09,357
or old abandoned playground had a really creepy atmosphere,

777
00:37:09,738 --> 00:37:11,820
we need to write in a way that evokes these ideas

778
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:14,002
instead of just throws them in the reader's face.

779
00:37:15,803 --> 00:37:19,647
So if we take those two key parts of those kind of ideas,

780
00:37:19,787 --> 00:37:21,889
we have using the unique strength of the medium

781
00:37:22,810 --> 00:37:24,972
and evoking drama and ideas in the audience's mind.

782
00:37:25,898 --> 00:37:28,699
And personally, I think pretty much every game that is kind of

783
00:37:29,159 --> 00:37:31,500
interesting from an interactive narrative point of view

784
00:37:32,180 --> 00:37:33,741
does at least one of these things well.

785
00:37:35,101 --> 00:37:37,462
Some games kind of naturally lean towards one or the other,

786
00:37:38,342 --> 00:37:39,883
but yeah, it does one of them, I find.

787
00:37:41,063 --> 00:37:44,925
And so first of all, a couple of, a few examples of using the unique strength of the medium.

788
00:37:47,106 --> 00:37:48,586
To me, like, the idea of...

789
00:37:49,931 --> 00:37:52,854
Well, of course, in interactive media,

790
00:37:53,254 --> 00:37:55,176
interactivity is the unique strength of the medium.

791
00:37:55,757 --> 00:37:58,780
And combining interactivity with narrative

792
00:37:59,300 --> 00:38:02,163
naturally leads us towards this idea of empowering the player

793
00:38:02,183 --> 00:38:04,866
to act with what I'll call narrative intentionality.

794
00:38:06,147 --> 00:38:07,588
I talked about intentionality earlier,

795
00:38:07,668 --> 00:38:11,232
but mostly in terms of gameplay and gameplay goals.

796
00:38:11,876 --> 00:38:14,297
But here we're talking about the idea of giving the player

797
00:38:14,337 --> 00:38:16,339
the information and the time and the opportunity

798
00:38:17,039 --> 00:38:19,701
to make intentional choices, but with narrative goals in mind

799
00:38:19,741 --> 00:38:20,701
and not just gameplay ones.

800
00:38:22,522 --> 00:38:24,724
I also mentioned how Dishonored and Immersive Sims revolve

801
00:38:24,744 --> 00:38:25,644
around intentionality.

802
00:38:26,225 --> 00:38:28,606
And this kind of goes for narrative intentionality, too.

803
00:38:29,469 --> 00:38:31,731
And this is on its case, especially like I'm so

804
00:38:31,791 --> 00:38:36,615
and it's on his case narrative intentionality is kind of go

805
00:38:36,655 --> 00:38:40,759
into the game the systems level in the sense that every NPC

806
00:38:40,799 --> 00:38:43,341
in the game can be you know you can even sneak around them

807
00:38:43,441 --> 00:38:44,983
or you can deal with them on leafly

808
00:38:45,063 --> 00:38:47,265
or you can know them horribly of course

809
00:38:47,525 --> 00:38:50,728
and we tell the players that this will change the story

810
00:38:50,768 --> 00:38:52,449
in the world and certain scenes in the game

811
00:38:52,969 --> 00:38:54,191
and the endings and the kind of thing.

812
00:38:54,984 --> 00:38:56,585
And so what this does is it transforms

813
00:38:56,625 --> 00:38:59,085
like a simple, what would be a simple gameplay choice

814
00:38:59,525 --> 00:39:00,786
into an opportunity to act

815
00:39:01,306 --> 00:39:02,986
and express narrative intentionality

816
00:39:03,486 --> 00:39:04,887
every time you encounter an NPC.

817
00:39:05,447 --> 00:39:07,668
That's the kind of thing we're into.

818
00:39:08,948 --> 00:39:10,368
Going back to the Dust District,

819
00:39:10,588 --> 00:39:11,809
one of the main things that appealed to me

820
00:39:11,849 --> 00:39:12,969
about this particular mission

821
00:39:13,449 --> 00:39:15,370
when I was kind of given the mission to work on

822
00:39:16,310 --> 00:39:18,330
is that its premise revolves around this idea

823
00:39:18,370 --> 00:39:20,971
of choosing a faction and making a choice

824
00:39:20,991 --> 00:39:22,211
that will affect the endings of the game.

825
00:39:23,253 --> 00:39:26,135
So the mission, the unique thing about the mission

826
00:39:26,195 --> 00:39:28,076
is this act of narrative intentionality

827
00:39:28,417 --> 00:39:30,038
kind of built into the whole premise of the mission.

828
00:39:31,439 --> 00:39:32,880
And with that kind of thing in mind,

829
00:39:32,900 --> 00:39:35,101
I mentioned in the world building section,

830
00:39:35,602 --> 00:39:37,583
these three scenes that I tried to develop

831
00:39:37,623 --> 00:39:38,544
the world with in some way.

832
00:39:39,104 --> 00:39:41,286
But another kind of aspect of it is that

833
00:39:41,846 --> 00:39:45,188
I deliberately designed them to kind of encourage

834
00:39:45,208 --> 00:39:47,590
the player to act with narrative intentionality.

835
00:39:48,731 --> 00:39:50,812
So two things about these scenes is that first of all,

836
00:39:50,832 --> 00:39:52,052
they're not just scenes that you watch.

837
00:39:52,832 --> 00:39:54,853
I'm not just showing and telling a story here.

838
00:39:55,413 --> 00:39:57,534
These scenes are deliberately designed to be interrupted

839
00:39:57,574 --> 00:39:58,655
and interacted with,

840
00:39:59,255 --> 00:40:01,596
and they all have extra lines and scripting and stuff

841
00:40:02,036 --> 00:40:05,637
beyond the main scene in order to react to certain choices

842
00:40:05,657 --> 00:40:06,398
that the player can make.

843
00:40:07,898 --> 00:40:09,499
And secondly, these scenes are there

844
00:40:09,539 --> 00:40:11,479
to present interesting dramatic situations

845
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,520
which invite the player to interact

846
00:40:13,560 --> 00:40:15,781
with narrative goals and values in mind

847
00:40:16,181 --> 00:40:17,061
and not just gameplay ones.

848
00:40:18,385 --> 00:40:19,606
you know, as far as I'm concerned,

849
00:40:19,666 --> 00:40:22,468
whenever I can make a player make gameplay choices

850
00:40:22,488 --> 00:40:23,369
that they're moving through a level

851
00:40:23,429 --> 00:40:25,851
with narrative goals in mind and not gameplay ones,

852
00:40:25,991 --> 00:40:28,213
it's kind of more interesting and, you know,

853
00:40:28,273 --> 00:40:29,795
cooler and more immersive and that kind of thing.

854
00:40:30,495 --> 00:40:32,777
And so, you know, any opportunity I can do,

855
00:40:33,578 --> 00:40:35,180
take to do that, I kind of try and take it.

856
00:40:37,115 --> 00:40:39,516
So that was about using the unique strength of the medium,

857
00:40:39,556 --> 00:40:43,478
which is agency and how that leads to narrative intentionality.

858
00:40:44,578 --> 00:40:47,159
If we take a look at the literature's take on this phrase,

859
00:40:47,620 --> 00:40:50,521
we have this idea of evoking drama and ideas in the audience's mind.

860
00:40:51,661 --> 00:40:52,202
And...

861
00:40:54,303 --> 00:40:56,103
Yeah, I've got an example of this.

862
00:40:56,143 --> 00:40:57,164
I've got three examples of this.

863
00:40:57,284 --> 00:41:00,525
The first one is a kind of low-level, in-the-moment kind of thing.

864
00:41:01,286 --> 00:41:02,486
It's a bit of a pet peeve of mine.

865
00:41:02,506 --> 00:41:02,926
When...

866
00:41:05,593 --> 00:41:09,154
like basically when something very dramatic and perilous is happening to

867
00:41:09,174 --> 00:41:13,696
the player character, but in the game it's presented as a cut scene, so

868
00:41:13,756 --> 00:41:17,677
control is taken away from the player just before it happens and so

869
00:41:17,697 --> 00:41:20,777
while the character is thinking, oh my god, I'm in peril, the player is thinking,

870
00:41:21,277 --> 00:41:24,198
oh, it's a cut scene, I can relax, I don't have to do anything and it's the

871
00:41:24,218 --> 00:41:27,699
complete opposite of what the character is supposed to be thinking. So it's just

872
00:41:27,719 --> 00:41:30,440
like, you know, I'm a big bit sensitive to this, it always drives me mad.

873
00:41:32,465 --> 00:41:35,207
By contrast, this scene from Uncharted 2,

874
00:41:35,767 --> 00:41:37,388
where you're navigating this collapsing building

875
00:41:37,428 --> 00:41:38,589
when the helicopter's blowing it up,

876
00:41:39,650 --> 00:41:42,612
is kind of a crazy, extreme, expensive example.

877
00:41:42,652 --> 00:41:43,112
It's amazing.

878
00:41:43,893 --> 00:41:46,775
But the cool thing here is that Nathan Drake

879
00:41:46,835 --> 00:41:48,136
is kind of cropping his pants and thinking,

880
00:41:48,196 --> 00:41:49,136
oh my God, what am I going to do?

881
00:41:49,557 --> 00:41:52,379
And the player is hopefully figuratively cropping their pants

882
00:41:52,739 --> 00:41:54,060
and thinking, oh my God, what am I going to do?

883
00:41:54,560 --> 00:41:57,182
And so they've perfectly spent a lot of money and time

884
00:41:57,602 --> 00:42:00,104
to align the player's thoughts with the character's thoughts

885
00:42:00,164 --> 00:42:01,665
in this dramatic situation.

886
00:42:02,965 --> 00:42:04,787
You know, it reminds me of this phrase by,

887
00:42:05,207 --> 00:42:08,189
quote from Frank Capra, who's like a filmmaker from the 30s,

888
00:42:08,229 --> 00:42:11,691
I think, who talked about how he made mistakes in drama.

889
00:42:12,352 --> 00:42:14,053
I thought drama was when actors cried,

890
00:42:14,513 --> 00:42:15,934
but drama is when the audience cries.

891
00:42:16,795 --> 00:42:20,077
And of course, we can take that idea and apply it to games,

892
00:42:20,097 --> 00:42:21,498
because we want the player's experience

893
00:42:21,558 --> 00:42:23,599
to be these dramatic highs and lows,

894
00:42:23,639 --> 00:42:25,881
and not just something they see on the screen.

895
00:42:28,162 --> 00:42:30,904
And my second example of evoking ideas is this

896
00:42:31,545 --> 00:42:33,667
classic pick up the can scene from Half-Life 2.

897
00:42:34,908 --> 00:42:37,350
For anyone who hasn't played it, well, first of all,

898
00:42:37,630 --> 00:42:39,312
shame on you, you should really play Half-Life 2.

899
00:42:39,372 --> 00:42:39,912
It's really good.

900
00:42:40,613 --> 00:42:43,415
But secondly, it's basically a tutorial for the player

901
00:42:43,435 --> 00:42:45,397
for picking up and interacting with physics objects.

902
00:42:45,997 --> 00:42:47,519
But what's cool is that the level designer

903
00:42:48,219 --> 00:42:51,562
used it as an opportunity to allow players

904
00:42:51,582 --> 00:42:53,364
to act with a narrative intentionality.

905
00:42:53,959 --> 00:42:59,151
you know between the when you pick up the can the game tells you that you can

906
00:42:59,371 --> 00:43:02,298
even put it in the in the trash can I can throw it at the combine guys head.

907
00:43:03,171 --> 00:43:07,455
And this choice between obeying and rebelling is a narrative thing

908
00:43:07,595 --> 00:43:11,979
that the player is going to consider when they go through this tutorial.

909
00:43:12,900 --> 00:43:15,762
But an extra cool thing about this is that these two particular choices,

910
00:43:16,683 --> 00:43:18,204
this idea of obeying and rebelling,

911
00:43:18,885 --> 00:43:24,169
basically sum up the human condition of people in the world of City 17.

912
00:43:24,710 --> 00:43:26,371
Every citizen here is struggling with this choice

913
00:43:26,391 --> 00:43:29,854
of whether or not they should obey and conform or resist and rebel.

914
00:43:30,901 --> 00:43:33,383
And so by being oppressed by the Combine directly

915
00:43:33,963 --> 00:43:35,584
and making this choice yourselves,

916
00:43:35,685 --> 00:43:37,446
the player relates to their plight, essentially,

917
00:43:37,466 --> 00:43:38,827
and relates to them as people.

918
00:43:39,708 --> 00:43:41,609
And so when you come up to this scene later in the game,

919
00:43:42,209 --> 00:43:43,190
you don't just shoot the baddies

920
00:43:43,270 --> 00:43:44,511
because they're baddies in a video game,

921
00:43:44,571 --> 00:43:46,473
but you naturally side with the civilians

922
00:43:46,533 --> 00:43:47,353
because you relate to them,

923
00:43:47,934 --> 00:43:49,415
and you're naturally opposed to the Combine

924
00:43:49,835 --> 00:43:52,477
based on a personal, interactive experience that came before.

925
00:43:53,713 --> 00:43:57,334
So even though Half-Life 2's story and gameplay is pretty linear and stuff,

926
00:43:58,054 --> 00:44:02,735
to me it still qualifies as solid, immersive, interactive storytelling

927
00:44:02,775 --> 00:44:05,495
because it's very smart about emotionally involving the player

928
00:44:05,515 --> 00:44:07,055
in the ideas and themes of the story.

929
00:44:09,056 --> 00:44:09,976
My final example is,

930
00:44:10,136 --> 00:44:13,197
it might be a surprise to immersive sim people

931
00:44:13,217 --> 00:44:16,637
because generally immersive sim people aren't so keen on this game,

932
00:44:17,798 --> 00:44:19,498
but I think this particular scene is amazing.

933
00:44:20,698 --> 00:44:21,898
So near the start of the game,

934
00:44:23,596 --> 00:44:26,577
It's establishing you as the main character, this father,

935
00:44:27,178 --> 00:44:29,859
in a game about losing your child and desperately wanting to save them,

936
00:44:29,959 --> 00:44:30,880
and doing anything to save them.

937
00:44:31,860 --> 00:44:35,723
And you're out in the garden, play-fighting in this very melodramatic,

938
00:44:35,743 --> 00:44:36,683
Star Wars kind of way,

939
00:44:37,504 --> 00:44:42,186
and as with a lot of Heavy Rain, it's a sequence of quick-time events,

940
00:44:42,927 --> 00:44:45,448
where you have a prompt to press the button on screen,

941
00:44:46,334 --> 00:44:50,964
And based on whether or not you succeed or fail at this,

942
00:44:51,626 --> 00:44:53,490
the game shows you a different animation, essentially.

943
00:44:54,793 --> 00:44:56,055
Now, the interesting thing here is that.

944
00:44:56,467 --> 00:44:59,148
if we follow our kind of gamer instincts

945
00:44:59,708 --> 00:45:01,028
to just try and win the sequence,

946
00:45:01,469 --> 00:45:03,670
we end up being a super douchey dad in the process.

947
00:45:04,370 --> 00:45:06,951
And this scene, like I've watched a lot of play-throughs

948
00:45:06,991 --> 00:45:08,091
of this on YouTube and stuff,

949
00:45:08,531 --> 00:45:10,412
and it's really good at making players realize this

950
00:45:10,572 --> 00:45:13,373
as they play and change the way they play

951
00:45:14,174 --> 00:45:15,634
based on this kind of narrative desire

952
00:45:15,694 --> 00:45:17,335
to play the role of a good dad.

953
00:45:18,295 --> 00:45:24,497
And so it's cool because it's like, you know, the subject of this scene is quite grand in the sense that it's,

954
00:45:25,517 --> 00:45:29,238
you know, it kind of reflects the fundamental nature of becoming a parent in the sense that

955
00:45:29,759 --> 00:45:33,620
when you have a kid, you know, it's like, it changes your life in a way that means that

956
00:45:34,020 --> 00:45:36,961
succeeding in your own kind of selfish terms is no longer the priority.

957
00:45:37,601 --> 00:45:40,042
And that's what this whole scene is about, it conveys interactively.

958
00:45:41,628 --> 00:45:43,830
So yeah, it's a great example of how we can take even

959
00:45:44,330 --> 00:45:46,292
something that seems kind of basic and binary

960
00:45:47,012 --> 00:45:49,895
and typically trivial as pressing a button in time,

961
00:45:50,555 --> 00:45:52,316
but use it to kind of interactively evoke

962
00:45:52,336 --> 00:45:54,618
some fairly big ideas about the story

963
00:45:54,758 --> 00:45:56,199
and about life in general even.

964
00:45:57,100 --> 00:45:58,681
And all of this is inside the player's mind

965
00:45:58,721 --> 00:46:01,964
without explicitly telling them anything, which is awesome.

966
00:46:03,906 --> 00:46:07,408
So to summarize, yeah, these are my three points

967
00:46:07,448 --> 00:46:08,789
about interactive narrative.

968
00:46:09,956 --> 00:46:12,077
Number one was striving to do more than just show and tell

969
00:46:12,217 --> 00:46:12,937
wherever possible.

970
00:46:14,138 --> 00:46:15,738
Number two was empowering the player

971
00:46:15,758 --> 00:46:17,259
to act with narrative intentionality.

972
00:46:18,219 --> 00:46:20,100
And or, depending on your kind of game,

973
00:46:20,760 --> 00:46:23,842
you can try and think of ways to evoke drama and story

974
00:46:23,882 --> 00:46:27,283
and ideas in the player's mind and not just on screen.

975
00:46:29,284 --> 00:46:31,425
And so we've got a couple of minutes.

976
00:46:31,825 --> 00:46:32,485
So yeah, to wrap up.

977
00:46:34,572 --> 00:46:37,353
As a closing thought, I thought about this particular section of a book called

978
00:46:37,393 --> 00:46:40,955
Understanding Comics by Scott McCloud, which is a super smart book that I

979
00:46:40,995 --> 00:46:41,675
recommend to everyone.

980
00:46:43,216 --> 00:46:46,998
It's kind of written to educate people and change people's perspective on

981
00:46:47,018 --> 00:46:50,720
comics, but I think it has the effect of doing this, changing the way we look at

982
00:46:50,740 --> 00:46:51,701
pretty much every medium.

983
00:46:51,761 --> 00:46:54,462
And I really recommend it to everyone if you like this kind of thing.

984
00:46:55,489 --> 00:46:57,731
And don't worry about reading the text on the panels here,

985
00:46:57,751 --> 00:47:01,013
but in this section of the book,

986
00:47:01,353 --> 00:47:03,034
he talks about how comics used to,

987
00:47:03,615 --> 00:47:06,497
and perhaps still do, suffer from people assuming

988
00:47:06,537 --> 00:47:09,699
that because comics are a medium made of pictures and words,

989
00:47:10,299 --> 00:47:12,521
that you can just take a great artist and a great writer

990
00:47:12,921 --> 00:47:13,982
and kind of just throw them together

991
00:47:14,042 --> 00:47:15,422
and you've got a great comic.

